data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit.

**APIs to remove:** `Thread.Abort()`, `Thread.ResetAbort()`, `catch (ThreadAbortException)`

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`). The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the
            // token fires before the task completes (.NET 6+ API).
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The above detects the timeout but **the delegate keeps running in the background** because cancellation is cooperative. If `work` must actually stop, pass the token into it:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;
    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

The caller then cooperates:

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is cooperative. If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep(ms)` won't wake on cancel. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Use async I/O overloads that accept tokens. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable` — always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter to distinguish your timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If the work is a third-party call you can't modify to accept a token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only safe forced-termination in modern .NET. |

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Why |
|----------------|--------|-----|
| `new Thread(…)` + `Start` | `Task.Run(…)` | Task-based model uses thread pool, avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellation-aware waiting (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timer) | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Different exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed — cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow |
